**Wynne Evans** (born 27 January 1972) is a [Welsh](/wiki/Wales "Wales")
[tenor](/wiki/Tenor "Tenor"). Known for his role as the tenor Gio Compario in
the [Gocompare.com](/wiki/Gocompare.com "Gocompare.com") insurance adverts on
[television in the United Kingdom](/wiki/Television_in_the_United_Kingdom
"Television in the United Kingdom"), he sang the role of Ubaldo Piangi in the
25th anniversary production of [Andrew Lloyd
Webber's](/wiki/Andrew_Lloyd_Webber "Andrew Lloyd Webber") _[The Phantom of
the Opera at the Royal Albert
Hall](/wiki/The_Phantom_of_the_Opera_at_the_Royal_Albert_Hall "The Phantom of
the Opera at the Royal Albert Hall")_.[1][2] He also responded to the New
Zealand [All Blacks](/wiki/All_Blacks "All Blacks")' [Haka](/wiki/Haka "Haka")
in 2004, singing '[Cwm Rhondda](/wiki/Cwm_Rhondda "Cwm Rhondda")'.[1] He went
on to sing at over 30 Welsh International rugby matches.[1] Evans, a lifelong
Spurs fan, also sang at Glory Glory Tottenham Hotspur at the last ever game at
White Hart Lane <http://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/the-lane-the-finale-
farewell-ceremony-may-14-140517/>. Missing or empty `|title=`

## Opera
singer[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Wynne_Evans&action=edit&section=1&editintro=Template:BLP_editintro
"Edit section: Opera singer")]

Born in [Carmarthen](/wiki/Carmarthen "Carmarthen"), [West
Wales](/wiki/West_Wales "West Wales"), Evans studied at the [Guildhall School
of Music and Drama](/wiki/Guildhall_School_of_Music_and_Drama "Guildhall
School of Music and Drama") and the [National Opera
Studio](/wiki/National_Opera_Studio "National Opera Studio").[1]

In late 2011 Evans was cast as the opera singer Ubaldo Piangi, in the 25th
Anniversary celebratory production of [Andrew Lloyd
Webber's](/wiki/Andrew_Lloyd_Webber "Andrew Lloyd Webber") _[The Phantom of
the Opera at the Royal Albert
Hall](/wiki/The_Phantom_of_the_Opera_at_the_Royal_Albert_Hall "The Phantom of
the Opera at the Royal Albert Hall")_[3]

Evans enjoys a close association with [Welsh National
Opera](/wiki/Welsh_National_Opera "Welsh National Opera")[4] where his roles
include Nemorino in _[L'elisir d'amore](/wiki/L%27elisir_d%27amore "L'elisir
d'amore")_,[5] Cassio in _[Otello](/wiki/Otello "Otello")_ (S4C Broadcast),[6]
The Duke in _[Rigoletto](/wiki/Rigoletto "Rigoletto")_ , Rodolfo in _[La
bohème](/wiki/La_boh%C3%A8me "La bohème")_ , Pedrillo in _[Die Entführung aus
dem Serail](/wiki/Die_Entf%C3%BChrung_aus_dem_Serail "Die Entführung aus dem
Serail")_ , Tamino in _[Die Zauberflöte](/wiki/Die_Zauberfl%C3%B6te "Die
Zauberflöte")_ , Alfredo in _[La traviata](/wiki/La_traviata "La traviata")_ ,
Jaquino in _[Leonore](/wiki/Leonore "Leonore")_ (BBC Broadcast), the
Schoolmaster in _[The Cunning Little Vixen](/wiki/The_Cunning_Little_Vixen
"The Cunning Little Vixen")_ , the Chevalier in _[Les Dialogues des
Carmelites](/wiki/Dialogues_of_the_Carmelites "Dialogues of the Carmelites")_
, the Italian Tenor in _[Der Rosenkavalier](/wiki/Der_Rosenkavalier "Der
Rosenkavalier")_ , the First Jew in _[Salome](/wiki/Salome_\(opera\) "Salome
\(opera\)")_ (S4C and BBC Broadcast), Liberto in _[L'incoronazione di
Poppea](/wiki/L%27incoronazione_di_Poppea "L'incoronazione di Poppea")_,
Brighella in _[Ariadne auf Naxos](/wiki/Ariadne_auf_Naxos "Ariadne auf
Naxos")_ and Alfred in _[Die Fledermaus](/wiki/Die_Fledermaus "Die
Fledermaus")_.[1]

He made his debut at the [Royal Opera House](/wiki/Royal_Opera_House "Royal
Opera House"), Covent Garden singing Vakula in the new production of
_[Cherevichki](/wiki/Cherevichki "Cherevichki")_.[1] In 2011 Evans sang in
[Mark-Anthony Turnage](/wiki/Mark-Anthony_Turnage "Mark-Anthony Turnage")'s
opera _[Anna Nicole](/wiki/Anna_Nicole "Anna Nicole")_ , based on the life of
[Anna Nicole Smith](/wiki/Anna_Nicole_Smith "Anna Nicole Smith") at the [Royal
Opera House](/wiki/Royal_Opera_House "Royal Opera House"), Covent Garden.

For [Opera de Lyon](/wiki/Opera_de_Lyon "Opera de Lyon") he has sung _[Gianni
Schicchi](/wiki/Gianni_Schicchi "Gianni Schicchi")_ , _[Il
Tabarro](/wiki/Il_Tabarro "Il Tabarro")_ and _[The Cunning Little
Vixen](/wiki/The_Cunning_Little_Vixen "The Cunning Little Vixen")_ For
[English National Opera](/wiki/English_National_Opera "English National
Opera") Evans has sung Alfredo in _[La Traviata](/wiki/La_Traviata "La
Traviata")_ , Spoletta and Cavaradossi in _[Tosca](/wiki/Tosca "Tosca")_ , and
Second Jew in _[Salome](/wiki/Salome_\(opera\) "Salome \(opera\)")_. For
[Opera North](/wiki/Opera_North "Opera North") he has appeared as Fenton in
_[Falstaff](/wiki/Falstaff_\(opera\) "Falstaff \(opera\)")_ , Prunier in _[La
Rondine](/wiki/La_rondine "La rondine")_ and Paulino in _[The Secret
Marriage](/wiki/The_Secret_Marriage "The Secret Marriage")_. For [Scottish
Opera](/wiki/Scottish_Opera "Scottish Opera") his roles include Tamino in
_[Die Zauberflöte](/wiki/Die_Zauberfl%C3%B6te "Die Zauberflöte")_ and the
Italian Tenor in _[Der Rosenkavalier](/wiki/Der_Rosenkavalier "Der
Rosenkavalier")_. For [Grange Park Opera](/wiki/Grange_Park_Opera "Grange Park
Opera") he has performed the roles of Trufaldino _[The Love for Three
Oranges](/wiki/The_Love_for_Three_Oranges "The Love for Three Oranges")_ the
Italian Tenor _[Capriccio](/wiki/Capriccio_\(opera\) "Capriccio \(opera\)")_
the Schoolmaster in '_[The Cunning Little
Vixen](/wiki/The_Cunning_Little_Vixen "The Cunning Little Vixen")_ and Harry
in _[La fanciulla del West](/wiki/La_fanciulla_del_West "La fanciulla del
West")_.[6] For the Classical Opera Company Evans sang the role of Fracasso in
_[La finta semplice](/wiki/La_finta_semplice "La finta semplice")_. Other
credits include Orpheus in _[Orpheus in the
Underworld](/wiki/Orpheus_in_the_Underworld "Orpheus in the Underworld")_ for
[Opera Holland Park](/wiki/Opera_Holland_Park "Opera Holland Park") and The
Peacock in [Param Vir](/wiki/Param_Vir "Param Vir")’s _Broken Strings_ for the
[Almeida Theatre](/wiki/Almeida_Theatre "Almeida Theatre"), which was recorded
for the [BBC](/wiki/BBC "BBC").[1]

## Concert
singer[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Wynne_Evans&action=edit&section=2&editintro=Template:BLP_editintro
"Edit section: Concert singer")]

As a concert singer Evans' appearances include [Vaughan
Williams](/wiki/Ralph_Vaughan_Williams "Ralph Vaughan Williams")' _[Serenade
to Music](/wiki/Serenade_to_Music "Serenade to Music")_ at the televised
opening night of the 2001 [BBC Proms](/wiki/The_Proms "The Proms"),
_[Beethoven's Ninth Symphony](/wiki/Symphony_No._9_\(Beethoven\) "Symphony No.
9 \(Beethoven\)")_ for [RTÉ](/wiki/RT%C3%89 "RTÉ"),
[Elgars](/wiki/Edward_Elgar "Edward Elgar")’s _[The Dream of
Gerontius](/wiki/The_Dream_of_Gerontius "The Dream of Gerontius")_ at the
[Welsh Proms](/wiki/Welsh_Proms "Welsh Proms"), the
[Verdi](/wiki/Giuseppe_Verdi "Giuseppe Verdi")
_[Requiem](/wiki/Requiem_\(Verdi\) "Requiem \(Verdi\)")_ at the [Royal Albert
Hall](/wiki/Royal_Albert_Hall "Royal Albert Hall") and a recital at the
[Wigmore Hall](/wiki/Wigmore_Hall "Wigmore Hall"), London.

Evans sings as a soloist on three CD volumes entitled ‘Here Come the
Classics’[7] with the [Royal Philharmonic
Orchestra](/wiki/Royal_Philharmonic_Orchestra "Royal Philharmonic Orchestra"),
has recorded _[Salome](/wiki/Salome_\(opera\) "Salome \(opera\)")_ and
[Ariadne auf Naxos](/wiki/Ariadne_auf_Naxos "Ariadne auf Naxos") for [Chandos
Records](/wiki/Chandos_Records "Chandos Records")[8] and has appeared several
times on the [BBC](/wiki/BBC "BBC")'s _[Friday Night is Music
Night](/wiki/Friday_Night_is_Music_Night "Friday Night is Music
Night")_.[1][9] He also presents on [BBC Radio Wales](/wiki/BBC_Radio_Wales
"BBC Radio Wales") with his brother, Mark Evans, and was awarded the MstJ by
[Queen Elizabeth II](/wiki/Queen_Elizabeth_II "Queen Elizabeth II") in 2008.

## Recording
artist[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Wynne_Evans&action=edit&section=3&editintro=Template:BLP_editintro
"Edit section: Recording artist")]

In 2010, Evans signed a six-album deal with [Warner Music](/wiki/Warner_Music
"Warner Music"); his first album is called _[A Song in My
Heart](/wiki/A_Song_in_My_Heart "A Song in My Heart")_ and was released on 21
March 2011. The album went straight to number one in the [UK Classical
Charts](/wiki/UK_Classical_Charts "UK Classical Charts") in the following
week.[10]

## Television and
radio[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Wynne_Evans&action=edit&section=4&editintro=Template:BLP_editintro
"Edit section: Television and radio")]

Since 2009 Evans has starred in an advertising campaign for
[UK](/wiki/United_Kingdom "United Kingdom") insurance comparison website
[Gocompare.com](/wiki/Gocompare.com "Gocompare.com"), playing the flamboyant,
operatic tenor Gio Compario.[11] He also appeared in a special version which
was part of the 2010 Channel 4 Comedy Gala raising money for [Great Ormond
Street Hospital](/wiki/Great_Ormond_Street_Hospital "Great Ormond Street
Hospital"), in which comedian [Jimmy Carr](/wiki/Jimmy_Carr "Jimmy Carr")
grabbed him by the [testicles](/wiki/Testicles "Testicles"), causing him to
sing in an even higher note.

In 2012, GoCompare launched the 'Saving the Nation' campaign starring Evans
again as Gio Compario. Evans made adverts in the series with [Sue
Barker](/wiki/Sue_Barker "Sue Barker"), [Stuart Pearce](/wiki/Stuart_Pearce
"Stuart Pearce"), [Ray Mears](/wiki/Ray_Mears "Ray Mears"), [Louis
Spence](/wiki/Louis_Spence "Louis Spence"), and most famously Professor
[Stephen Hawking](/wiki/Stephen_Hawking "Stephen Hawking") with all of them
trying to kill him and thus save the nation from his singing about
GoCompare.[12]

In 2011, Evans began presenting. He presented a programme about the
[Eisteddfod](/wiki/National_Eisteddfod_of_Wales "National Eisteddfod of
Wales") for the [BBC](/wiki/BBC "BBC") and his own TV show on [S4C](/wiki/S4C
"S4C"). In 2012, Evans became a regular presenter on [BBC Radio
Wales](/wiki/BBC_Radio_Wales "BBC Radio Wales") and from October 2013 Evans
presented a weekly Friday afternoon show called 'Wynne Evans' Big Welsh
Weekend'. Since February 2016, he has presented an entertainment show on the
station from 11am-1pm every weekday.

Evans was also one of eight celebrities chosen to participate in an intense
week of learning Welsh at a campsite in Pembrokeshire for the series
[cariad@iaith:love4language](/wiki/Cariad@iaith:love4language
"Cariad@iaith:love4language") shown on S4C in May 2012.

In 2012, Evans presented _The Guide to Opera_ on [Classic
FM](/wiki/Classic_FM_\(UK\) "Classic FM \(UK\)"). The show was subsequently
nominated for an Arqiva award. In 2013 Evans became a regular presenter on
Classic FM

In August 2012, Evans appeared on the football show _[Soccer
AM](/wiki/Soccer_AM "Soccer AM")_. He went on the show again in August 2013.

In March 2015, Evans appeared in the [Sky 1](/wiki/Sky_1 "Sky 1") comedy drama
_[Stella](/wiki/Stella_\(UK_TV_series\) "Stella \(UK TV series\)")_ , as a
candidate running for council / Mexican wrestler. The episode ended with Evans
singing a couple of numbers.

In July 2015, Evans returned as Gio Compario once more, in a new GoCompare
commercial. Now embraced by the British populace, he performs at an arena to
huge cheers and the words "He's Back..."are seen at the end of the
advertisement.[13]

##
Awards[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Wynne_Evans&action=edit&section=5&editintro=Template:BLP_editintro
"Edit section: Awards")]

Evans was made a member of the [Gorsedd](/wiki/Gorsedd "Gorsedd") of the Bards
of Wales in 2012 [14] and an Honorary Fellow of the [University of Wales
Trinity Saint David](/wiki/University_of_Wales_Trinity_Saint_David "University
of Wales Trinity Saint David") in 2013.[15] He was also made a Member of the
[Venerable Order of Saint John](/wiki/Venerable_Order_of_Saint_John "Venerable
Order of Saint John") by HM The Queen in 2008.

## Personal
life[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Wynne_Evans&action=edit&section=6&editintro=Template:BLP_editintro
"Edit section: Personal life")]

Evans is a trustee of The Elizabeth Evans Trust.[16] Evans' mother was
Elizabeth Evans [MBE](/wiki/Order_of_the_British_Empire "Order of the British
Empire"), who founded and ran both The Carmarthen Youth Opera and The Lyric
Theatre in [Carmarthen](/wiki/Carmarthen "Carmarthen") for 25 years. She died
in 2004 and subsequently Evans and his two brothers founded the Trust.

Evans has two children - Ismay Evans and Taliesin Evans.
